Holy cow am I over the moon. This past week I came to New Zealand in hopes to harvest a big Sika stag & yesterday I got my opportunity. Chasing after a hot doe he was roaring his head off. Crawling up the mountain side & on my knees, I set up against the thick brush, begging him to show himself on the ridge. 45 yards later, & the rest was history! 😤

After chasing fallow for five days straight, I was finally able to send an arrow through this stud. My brother & I inched our way over the mountain from where we spotted him from another ridge. We set up below him knowing he’d eventually walk out from behind the brush. Drawing back, he stepped out into view & I let my grim reaper eat. 
Really happy to be leaving NZ with a beautiful buck & a beast of a Sika stag. Now it’s time to get back to the states to chase after a few more turkeys. 🙌🏽

2023 pronghorn spot n stalk ✔️ 🏹 
September has been tough on me. Three states, three tags, & lots of hiking. A big goal of mine was to kill my first pronghorn on foot, spot & stalking through the high plains of north eastern Wyoming. This big bully was in full rut, bedding 10 of his does, & running off any buck that came his way. Grabbing my decoy, I spotted this guy from about 500 yards away, & went after him. Closing the distance, I had my bow in one hand & dragged my decoy in the other. My buddy Nate stayed about 80 yards behind me jumping from one hay bail to the other, camera in hand. Slowly making my way over the ridge, I spotted his horns coming directly at me in a full on sprint. Drawing back my bow, & attempting to keep the decoy from falling over, he stopped at 45 yards & I let an arrow fly. I’m happy as could be! Big thanks to my friends Rick & Amy over at @rawhidecreekoutfitters for letting me come out & hunt. Some of the best people out there! I’m going home very happy y’all. Woohoo

Sweet November rut didn’t let me down! Dad & I looked on our @onxhunt map looking at pinch points earlier this week. With a south west wind I was confident on where I wanted to sit… making our way to the stand we bumped a big boy bedded down in the corn.. not too upset we had a feeling that we were in the right place to be. When I got into my @summitstands a big boy walked by at 70 yards but into the woods behind us.. we snort wheezed & grunted a couple of times trying to get his attention… he didn’t fall for the bait. As the sun started to creep below the trees, the does slowly made their way into the picked corn field below me, uneasy.
Luey, a main frame 9 pointer with a bunch of junk stepped out into the field looking for a hot doe. I instantly recognized him as the buck I saw earlier in the sit. Drawing back my bow I knew he was approximately 30 yards & let it rip!! WHACK! Right into a corner stalk!!!! I about died inside as I started to feel the sorrow building up. To my luck, he stopped at the end of the field staring in my direction at about 55 yards. Turning his head & stomping off, I quickly knocked another arrow… luey blew & I let the grim reaper fly.. the rest is history! 🦌 🏹

The journey after Luey has been hard this year, but we got him! 🦌 🏹
